Wine Quality

About the dataset¶

This repository has two datasets of red and white wine samples which consists of inputs includes objective tests

Objective

  1. To analyze the features for positive and negative coorelation
  2. To know about the outliers present in the dataset using box plot
  3. Using Support vector machines and Naive Bayes algorithm to classify the wine quality

Data Features¶

Thus we have seen dimensions of the data, both the dataset has same number of variables but white wine has almost thrice the amount of observations then the red wine dataset. Each wine sample (row) has the following characteristics (columns):

  • Fixed acidity
  • Volatile acidity
  • Citric acid
  • Residual sugar
  • Chlorides
  • Free sulfur dioxide
  • Total sulfur dioxide
  • Density
  • pH
  • Sulphates
  • Alcohol
  • Quality (score between 0 and 10)

In [10]:
def custom_style(title, xlab, ylab, width = 400, height = 300):
    p = figure(plot_width = width, plot_height = height, title = title, x_axis_label = xlab, y_axis_label = ylab)
    p.title.text_font_size = "10pt"
    p.title.align = "center"
    p.xaxis.axis_label_text_font_size = "10pt"
    p.yaxis.axis_label_text_font_size = "10pt"
    return p

def custom_barplot(data, width = 400, height = 300, color = "#3687cc", title = "Barplot", xlab = "Category",
                   ylab = "Counts"):
    counts = data.value_counts()
    p = custom_style(width = width, height = height, title = title, xlab = xlab, ylab = ylab)
    p.vbar(x = counts.index, top = counts.values, width = 0.5, bottom = 0,  color = color)
    return show(p)

Correlation¶

In [13]:
def coorelation_matrix_plot(data, title = "Red Wine Correlation Matrix", height = 9, width = 12):
    cor_mat = round(data.corr(method ="spearman"), 2)
    plt.figure(figsize = (width, height))
    ax = sns.heatmap(cor_mat, annot=True, annot_kws={"size": 15}, cmap = sns.color_palette("PuOr_r", 50), 
                     vmin = -1, vmax = 1)
    ax.axes.set_title(title, fontsize = 30)
    ax.title.set_position([.5, 1.03])
    plt.show()
    
coorelation_matrix_plot(wine_red_df.iloc[:,:-1], title = "Red Wine Correlation Matrix")

Heatmap shows the correlation between the variables in the dataset. High concentration of color representation high corrlation. Brown represents positive and purple represents negative correlation.

From the above heatmap on the red wine, we have the following inference

  • It looks like we have pH and fixed acidity has inverse relationships between them. The same in case of citric acid and volatile acidity too.
  • There is a strong positive relationship between total sulfur dioxide and free sulfur dioxide.

Negative relation (Increase in this will increase the quality)¶

  • Alcohol and Density having very High coorelation value of -0.82

Positive relation (Increase in this will decrease the quality)¶

  • Density and Residual Sugar have very high coorelation value of 0.78
  • Free sulphur dioxide and total sulphur dioxide have fair coorelation value of 0.62
  • Density and chlorides and Total sulphur dioxide have fair coorelation value.

def box_plot(data, height = 10, width = 16, title = "Boxplot"):
    plt.figure(figsize=(width, height))
    plt.suptitle(title, y = 0.94, fontsize = 30)
    sns.set(font_scale = 2)
    sns.boxplot(data = data, orient = "h")

Removing the outliers¶

In [19]:
# For each feature find the data points with extreme high or low values
outliers_data_red = pd.DataFrame()
outliers_data_white = pd.DataFrame()
length = 0
for feature in wine_red_df.keys():
    # Calculate Q1 (25th percentile of the data) for the given feature
    Q1 = np.percentile(wine_red_df[feature], q=25)
    
    # Calculate Q3 (75th percentile of the data) for the given feature
    Q3 = np.percentile(wine_red_df[feature], q=75)
    
    # Use the interquartile range to calculate an outlier step (1.5 times the interquartile range)
    interquartile_range = Q3 - Q1
    step = 1.5 * interquartile_range
    
    # Display the outliers
    print("Outliers considered for the red white")
    print("Data points considered outliers for the feature '{}':".format(feature))
    outliers_data_red = outliers_data_red.append(wine_red_df[~((wine_red_df[feature] >= Q1 - step) & (wine_red_df[feature] <= Q3 + step))])
    outliers_data_white = outliers_data_white.append(wine_white_df[~((wine_white_df[feature] >= Q1 - step) & (wine_white_df[feature] <= Q3 + step))])
    display(wine_red_df[~((wine_red_df[feature] >= Q1 - step) & (wine_red_df[feature] <= Q3 + step))])
    print("----------------------------------------------------------------------")
    print("Outliers considered for the white white")
    print("Data points considered outliers for the feature '{}':".format(feature))
    display(wine_white_df[~((wine_white_df[feature] >= Q1 - step) & (wine_white_df[feature] <= Q3 + step))])

def svm_accuracy_cv(X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test, n_fold = 10):
    best_score = 0
    best_C = 10000
    C_list = [1, 10, 100, 1000]
    for C in C_list:
        svc = svm.SVC(C = C, kernel = 'rbf')
        # Getting the scores on n folds
        scores = cross_val_score(svc, X_train, y_train, cv = n_fold)
        score = scores.mean()
        if score > best_score:
            best_C = C
            best_score = score

    svc = svm.SVC(C = best_C, kernel = "rbf")
    svc.fit(X_train, y_train)
    accuracy = svc.score(X_test, y_test)
    return accuracy, best_C

            best_score = score
